ually small grocery stores). African Americans in Los Angeles have sustained few long-term boycotts of Korean American businesses—but the absence of "routine" contention there goes hand in hand with the large-scale riots of 1992 and continuous acts of individual violence.In demonstrating how conflicts between these groups were intimately tied to their political surroundings, this book yields practical lessons for the future. City governments can do little to fight widening economic inequality in an increasingly diverse nation, Joyce writes. But officials and activists can restructure political institutions to provide the foundations for new multiracial coalitions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxRelations with Korean Americans. 0aAfrican AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial conditions. 0aAfrican AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxSocial conditions. 0aKorean AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial conditions. 0aKorean AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxSocial conditions. 0aSocial conflictzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aSocial conflictzNew York (State)zNew York. 4aAfrican Hist & Diaspora. 4aDiscrimination & Race Relations. 4aUrban Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173136540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501731365423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501731365/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPD